{% extends "layouts/catalog.html.jinja" %}
{% from "components/card.html.jinja" import card %}
{% from "components/typography.html.jinja" import typography %}
{% from "includes/page-header.html.jinja" import render_page_header %}

{% block title %}Skills - Moo UI{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <article class="moo-doc-page">
    {{ render_page_header(
      "Skills",
      "Project-aware instructions for coding agents that generate or update Moo UI components.",
      id="skills-title"
    ) }}

    <section class="moo-doc-section" aria-labelledby="skills-roadmap-title">
      {{ typography("What Skills Are For", variant="section-title", id="skills-roadmap-title") }}
      <p>
        A Moo UI skill gives a coding agent the context it needs before it
        touches the catalog: Bootstrap is the public contract, shadcn is the
        visual reference point, and HTML stays first-class for server-rendered
        products.
      </p>
      <p>
        The goal is simple: an agent should be able to add a component, improve
        an example, or compose a block without breaking Bootstrap markup,
        documented plugin behavior, Sass variables, or the visual rhythm of the
        system.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="moo-doc-section" aria-labelledby="skills-context-title">
      {{ typography("What Agents Should Know", variant="section-title", id="skills-context-title") }}
      <div class="moo-doc-card-grid">
        {% call card(extra_class="h-100", body_class="d-grid gap-2") %}
          <h3 class="h5 mb-0">Bootstrap first</h3>
          <p class="text-body-secondary mb-0">
            Prefer Bootstrap markup, classes, variables, and
            <code>data-bs-*</code> APIs before adding Moo-owned surface area.
          </p>
        {% endcall %}

        {% call card(extra_class="h-100", body_class="d-grid gap-2") %}
          <h3 class="h5 mb-0">Taste, not source</h3>
          <p class="text-body-secondary mb-0">
            Study shadcn/ui for spacing, restraint, and interaction feel, but
            write original examples and keep the implementation Bootstrap-native.
          </p>
        {% endcall %}

        {% call card(extra_class="h-100", body_class="d-grid gap-2") %}
          <h3 class="h5 mb-0">Verify before ready</h3>
          <p class="text-body-secondary mb-0">
            A component is ready only after tests, generated examples, light and
            dark states, and browser behavior all match the catalog contract.
          </p>
        {% endcall %}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="moo-doc-section" aria-labelledby="skills-workflow-title">
      {{ typography("Expected Workflow", variant="section-title", id="skills-workflow-title") }}
      <p>
        Start from the existing component page, read the related macro and Sass
        files, then compare the live output with Bootstrap behavior and the Moo
        UI visual language. Keep changes additive when possible, and preserve
        existing class names unless a contract change is intentional.
      </p>
      <p>
        Skills for Moo UI will document these checks in a reusable form so
        future components can be built with the same discipline: inspect first,
        keep Bootstrap native, verify in the browser, and update docs with the
        same language as the public README.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
{% endblock %}
